In France, voting is a low-technological experience in France: voters isolate themselves in a cover, put in advance a printed sheet of paper with their chosen candidate in envelope.
Once the authorities have checked the voter’s identity, he releases the envelope in the ballot box and signs it on the ballot list.
The French electoral law of France strictly defines the proceedings.
Since 1988, ballot boxes must be transparent, for voters and observers to be witnesses that there are no envelopes in them at the beginning of the vote, and that no other envelopes will be added except those of the properly numbered and authorized voters.
