When a small group of living beings (a small population) separates from the main population from which it originates (for example, if it moves through a mountain range or river or if it moves to a new island and cannot easily go back), it is often found in an environment different from that in which it was previously.
This new environment has different resources and different rivals, so the new population will need different traits or adaptations to be a strong rival compared to what it needed before.
The original population has not changed at all, they still need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, the new population begins to adapt to its new environment and begins to look less like the other population.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they can no longer be called the same species.
This process is called speciation, which means the formation of new species. Widowage is an inevitable consequence and a very significant part of evolution.
